## Change 2: FAQ Section — New Component

### Where it goes
Insert the FAQ section **between the case studies / recent work section and the existing "Send me your problem" CTA section**. It should not appear below the form. This placement follows the visitor's decision journey: understand the model → feel seen by the pain points → believe it works (case studies) → remove final objections (FAQ) → submit.

### Format
**Static, fully expanded** — not an accordion. All questions and answers visible without interaction. Rationale: the ICP is not highly technical, is slightly skeptical, and should not have to work to see reassurance. Every answer is short enough that static display does not create a length problem.

### Section structure
```
[Section label: "COMMON QUESTIONS" — small caps, muted, same style as other section labels]
[Section headline: "Before you hit send."]
[Subhead optional: omit if it feels redundant with the questions themselves]
[FAQ grid: two-column on desktop, single-column on mobile]
```

The headline "Before you hit send." is intentional — it acknowledges the visitor is close to submitting and positions the FAQ as a pre-send checklist, not a generic help section.

### Layout
- Two-column grid on desktop (4 questions left, 4 questions right)
- Single column on mobile
- Each Q&A is a discrete unit — question in bold/semi-bold DM Sans, answer in regular weight below it
- Subtle divider or spacing between each unit — no heavy card borders. Match the visual lightness of the existing site.
- Section sits on the cream/off-white background, not inside a dark card

### Questions and answers (use verbatim)

**Do I have to know what the solution is?**
No. Most people who reach out know something isn't working — they just can't put a name to it. Figuring that out is what the free plan is for.

**What happens after I submit?**
I read it and respond within 24 hours. You get a plain-English plan — what I'd do, how long it takes, what it costs. No call required to get that far.

**What kinds of problems can you help with?**
The kind that have been on your list for months. A report nobody can pull without exporting to Excel. A process three people do manually that nobody has time to fix. A system you're paying for that half the team doesn't use. If it's slowing your business down, send it.

**What does it cost?**
The plan is free. If you want me to execute it, you get a flat project price — one number, approved before anything starts. No hourly clock, no surprises mid-project.

**What if you can't help?**
I'll tell you straight, and point you somewhere better if I can. Some problems are the wrong fit for what I do — and you'll hear that for free rather than find out after paying someone else.

**What if the plan isn't what I was expecting?**
Tell me. Plans aren't binding — they're a starting point. If something's off, we talk through it before anything begins. You're not committed to anything until you say so.

**Is there any commitment involved?**
None. Submitting a problem doesn't start a project. Reading the plan doesn't start a project. You decide if and when anything moves forward.

**How is the free plan actually viable?**
Two years ago this model didn't work — understanding a problem well enough to return a real plan took hours of calls and back-and-forth. AI has changed that. I can triage a submission and produce a genuine, actionable plan in a fraction of the time. The cost of that step dropped, so I stopped charging for it. You get a real answer before spending anything.

### Typography treatment
- Question text: DM Sans, ~15-16px, semi-bold or bold, near-black
- Answer text: DM Sans, ~14-15px, regular weight, slightly muted (not full black — match the existing body copy tone)
- Section label: Same small-caps muted style as "RECENT WORK", "PRICING", etc.
- Headline "Before you hit send.": Lora serif, same scale as other section headlines

